<dl id="n01013a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01013a">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01013a"> 13(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> condign satisfaction / &mdash; <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n01013a"><li>FW 172.29 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n01013a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n01013a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n01013a">MS BL 47471b-51</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:333 <a name="g10d" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#g10d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/g10d.htm#n01013a">Draft: I.7&sect;1.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> However, Moore was hot for a deadly reprisal, and, by the hand of his trusty, though eccentric, friend, Hume, he dispatched to Jeffrey a fiery cartel, demanding a plenary apology, or that <mark>condign satisfaction</mark> which one gentleman is bound to accord another, etc. <small> Michael Monahan, <a name="MMNH" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MMNH"><cite title="source">Nova Hibernia</cite></a> (1914) [THOMAS MOORE] 108</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: condign: worthily deserved, merited; as in &lsquo;condign punishment&rsquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
